This prose work, undertaken at the request of a successor of Cuthbert'S, Eadfrid, and of the monks of Lindis- farne, adopts here and there the language of an earlier work of Beda's, a poem DE MmAcvms s CVTHBERTI. It is not however a mere version of this latter, but an independent work, 1 5 as appears even from the presace. Beda, as he there assures us, had taken all pains to report the truth, having first com- municated his manuscript to some monks long intimate with Cuthbert, and then submitted a copy revised in accordance with their judgement to the criticism of a meeting of elders and 20 teachers of Lindisfarne monastery, who however found nothing further to alter. The difference between the subject-matter of the prose life and the poem is correctly indicated by their titles ε in the latter only the miracles are recorded, while the former embraces in additionthe remainder of the saint’s life. Beda 25 had indeed promised such a supplement in the preface to his poem.
